knowledge_graph.title: Breast milk
knowledge_graph.description: Breast milk or mother's milk is milk produced by the mammary glands in the breast of human females. Breast milk is the primary source of nutrition for newborn infants, comprising fats, proteins, carbohydrates, and a varying composition of minerals and vitamins.

related_questions.question: Can breasts lactate without being pregnant?
related_questions.snippet: Sometimes a woman's breasts make milk even though she is not pregnant or breastfeeding. This condition is called galactorrhea (say: guh-lack-tuh-ree-ah). The milk may come from one or both breasts. It may leak on its own or only when the breasts are touched.
related_questions.title: Galactorrhea: What You Should Know About It - AAFP

related_questions.question: What is special about human milk?
related_questions.snippet: Human breast milk contains carbohydrates, protein, fat, vitamins, minerals, digestive enzymes and hormones. In addition to these nutrients, it is rich in immune cells, including macrophages, stem cells, and numerous other bioactive molecules.

related_questions.snippet: So, When Does Breast Milk Come In? Though colostrum production begins as early as 16 weeks pregnant and should begin to be expressed right away after birth (with some moms even experiencing occasional leakage later in pregnancy), its look and composition differs significantly from your later breast milk.

related_questions.question: What is the first milk of human?
related_questions.snippet: Colostrum is the first form of breastmilk that is released by the mammary glands after giving birth. It's nutrient-dense and high in antibodies and antioxidants to build a newborn baby's immune system. It changes to breast milk within two to four days after your baby is born.

buttons.subtitle: Is Breast Milk Healthy?
buttons.title: Breast Milk Is Best | Johns Hopkins Medicine
buttons.snippet: Breastmilk has the nutrients that are best for your baby's brain growth and nervous system development. Studies of breastfed babies have found that they do better on intelligence tests when they grow older. A breastfed baby's eyes also work better. This is mostly because of certain types of fat in breastmilk.
snippet_highlighted_words: Breastmilk has the nutrients that are best for your baby's brain growth and nervous system development

buttons.subtitle: Why Is Breast Milk So Good For Babies?
buttons.title: Why is Breastfeeding Important for your Baby?
buttons.snippet: Breast milk helps keep your baby healthy. It protects against allergies, sickness, and obesity. It protects against diseases, like diabetes and cancer. It protects against infections, like ear infections. It is easily digested – no constipation, diarrhea or upset stomach.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Breast Milk Taste Like?
buttons.title: What does breast milk taste like? | BabyCenter
buttons.snippet: The flavor of breast milk varies, but it's most often described as very sweet. It contains water, fat, carbohydrates (lactose), proteins, vitamins and minerals, and amino acids. It's the lactose – which makes up about 7% of breast milk – that makes it taste like sugar.

buttons.subtitle: How Much Protein Is In Breast Milk?
buttons.title: Review of Infant Feeding: Key Features of Breast Milk and ... - NCBI
buttons.snippet: During early lactation, the protein content in human milk ranges from 1.4–1.6 g/100 mL, to 0.8–1.0 g/100 mL after three to four months of lactation, to 0.7–0.8 g/100 mL after six months [11,12]. The fat content varies significantly with maternal diet and is also positively related to weight gain during pregnancy.
snippet_highlighted_words: 1.4–1.6 g/100 mL, to 0.8–1.0 g/100 mL after three to four months of lactation, to 0.7–0.8 g/100 mL after six months

buttons.subtitle: What Type Of Milk Is Breast Milk?
buttons.title: What's in Breast Milk? | American Pregnancy Association
buttons.snippet: Human milk contains two types of proteins: whey and casein. Approximately 60% is whey, while 40% is casein. This balance of the proteins allows for quick and easy digestion. If artificial milk, also called formula, has a greater percentage of casein, it will be more difficult for the baby to digest.

buttons.subtitle: Storing Breast Milk
buttons.title: Breast milk storage: Do's and don'ts - Mayo Clinic
buttons.snippet: Freshly expressed breast milk can be stored in the back of the refrigerator for up to four days in clean conditions. However, it's optimal to use or freeze the milk within three days. Deep freezer. Freshly expressed breast milk can be stored in the back of a deep freezer for up to 12 months.
snippet_highlighted_words: in the back of the refrigerator for up to four days in clean conditions

buttons.subtitle: Breastmilk Guidelines
buttons.title: Breast Milk Storage and Preparation | Breastfeeding - CDC
list: At room temperature (77°F or colder) for up to 4 hours.
In the refrigerator for up to 4 days.
In the freezer for about 6 months is best; up to 12 months is acceptable. Recommended storage times are important to follow for best quality.
